<section id="platforms-wide-section">
    <!-- Main Title with Theme Colors -->
    <h2 class="platforms-main-title">PROJECTS & <span class="highlight-platforms">PLATFORMS</span></h2>

    <!-- Vertical Container for the Stacked Cards -->
    <div class="platforms-vertical-container">
        
        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">Pairfect Square</h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">Pairfect Square is a single-day networking event for COS students to meet others with similar study habits. It is a matching initiative that pairs FOCUS 2024 students based on study habits, schedules, academic goals, and course load, with participants completing a pre-event form to determine their most compatible match. Rather than functioning purely as a social mixer, Pairfect Square aims to establish networking and academic support systems by connecting students who can study, review, and grow together throughout the term.</p>
        </div>
    
        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">AtCOSphere</h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">AtCOSphere is a single-day batch mixer that provides a non-academic space for FOCUS 2024 students to interact across departments. The event features games and food, with home organizations promoting departmental and upcoming activities to the wider batch, aiming to foster a unified COS community by creating shared experiences outside the academic setting. </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Platform Card 3 -->
        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">FORGE – Forum for Research Growth and Excellence </h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">FORGE is a mock research congress where COS students can present their personal projects and research. Students will be able to practice interpersonal relations on a more formal level, giving them access to support and peer-reviewing experiences, all while platforming student ideas and encouraging students to start scientific dialogue.</p>
        </div>

         <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">COS Effect</h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">COS Effect is a structured student concerns and sentiment management system built around two tracks: a concerns track for issues requiring resolution, and a sentiment track for proactive pulse-checking on the batch's needs. Concerns are raised through centralized forms, logged on a tracker dashboard, and assigned to a designated Student Services representative within the day. Admin-level concerns are escalated through FOCUS2024, while non-urgent matters are handled at the rep level, with resolution within 1–2 working days. An anonymous channel is available for sentiments students prefer not to be identified. Regular pulse checks gauge batch needs before concerns escalate. At the end of each semester, a transparency report summarizing concerns raised, actions taken, and recurring issues is published through the batch newsletter.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title"> Project INFORM: Information on Forms, Requests, and Matters  </h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">Project INFORM is a recurring series of information sessions discussing academic policies, forms, and procedures relevant in the third year. The sessions cover processes for absences, grade consultations, course retaking, shifting, and other common administrative concerns. Returning student processes and newly introduced policies are also addressed, with certain sessions tailored by program where policies differ, recorded for asynchronous access, and paired with a running FAQ document updated each term.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">Theory of Reviewtivity</h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">Theory of Reviewtivity is a peer tutoring and academic review program developed in partnership with home organizations, SSC-SHINE, and the Lasallian Scholars Society (LSS). Tutors are matched to requested courses, and NMAT review sessions are also provided through a collaboration with a tutoring academy.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">Brewster’s Law</h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">Brewster’s Law is a recurring coffee-session series held once per term, where students engage in casual conversations with students, faculty, alumni, researchers, and professionals on contemporary scientific and national issues. A "Coffee with an Alumni/Researcher/Professional" sub-format will be present here to directly expose students to career journeys and realities in Philippine science. </p>
        </div>

        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">Duel Space</h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">Duel Space is a structured debate series held once per term with differing themes, where students examine contemporary scientific and policy issues through respectful, evidence-based discourse. Formats will include debates, round-robin tournaments, and inter-program debates between students. Expert judges (faculty, professionals, or speakers) ensure that factual accuracy. Every debate motion receives a SCIclopedia fact-check post-event to correct any misinformation that surfaced during debates.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">Sciclopedia</h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">Monthly newsletter posted on socials that keeps the batch updated on FOCUS2024 projects. It is a centralized science knowledge hub that translates complex Philippine science developments into student-friendly content, covering Philippine science updates, national policy explainers, science misinformation breakdowns, an Opportunities Corner featuring DOST programs, scholarships, fellowships, and conferences, Filipino scientist spotlights (Future of Filipino Science), and post-debate fact-checks from Duel Space events. We will also feature current research of professors and others in all of the departments, as well as transparency reports and updates on upcoming events.</p>
        </div>

    </div>

    <br><br><br> 

    <h2 class="platforms-main-title">LA <span class="highlight-platforms" style="color: #41D3BD">AGENDA</span></h2>

    <div class="platforms-vertical-container">
        
        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">A Bill Establishing Tuition Fee Transparency</h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">This bill seeks to work in coordination with the DLSU Administration and OUR to restore and maintain an accessible, up-to-date glossary of tuition fee terms, one that was previously available but has since become outdated and inaccessible due to the migration to Archers Hub. To ensure lasting accountability, the glossary would be updated every academic year, and a formal process would be established through which students can raise questions or concerns about specific charges.</p>
        </div>
    
        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">A Bill Establishing the Learning Modality Consultation and Impact Review</h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">To ensure that the learning modality adjustment effective Term 1 AY 2026-2027 is met with meaningful student participation and institutional accountability, this bill coordinates with the DLSU Administration and academic departments to expand on the Academics Council's February 13, 2026 consultations by establishing a broader statistical basis for student sentiment. This bill aims to launch a student impact review at the start of Term 2 in coordination with the DLSU USG. By gathering student feedback through surveys, forums, and Focus Group Discussions on how Term 1 has affected your grades, commute burdens, additional expenses, and campus crowding, the Legislative Assembly will publish a public report and formally demand that the admin at least consider the student body in the decision and the effect it had and reconsider the 50% hybrid or at least ease the burden of the students most affected by the change going forward. </p>
        </div>

        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">A Bill Establishing a Lasallian Campus Meal Subsidy</h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">Establishes a USG-funded subsidized meal program providing eligible DLSU students a fixed discount on one meal per week across the DLSU-operated canteen in the LS Building, covering the weeks of each term, excluding ILW and Exam weeks. This specifically targets students who are financially struggling or disproportionately burdened by the additional on-campus day resulting from the 75% F2F attendance shift. The once-a-week subsidy scope is intentional to address the additional campus day, aimed to ease the burdens of students who are now required to spend an additional day in campus. Funded by the USG.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">An Ordinance Implementing Undergraduate COS Syllabus Accessibility </h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">Coordinates with the Science College Government that the syllabi for all COS courses be published by the end of the prior term across all official and batch government platforms, in coordination with each COS Department. At the very minimum, all syllabi must include major course topics so students can prepare for the topics before enrollment during their term break.</p>
        </div>

    </div>


</section>